    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-13T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-13T10:00:00-05:00" n="616"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d616">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.62/795: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-13T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 13, 1940—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4700. My 4684, November 12, 6 p.m.<note n="51" xml:id="d616fn51">Not
                        printed.</note> Molotov was the guest of honor at a party given by
                    Ribbentrop last night at the Kaiserhof Hotel for members of the Soviet
                    delegation and Embassy and German officials. Today he was received for a long
                    conversation by Goering and also called upon Hess.<note n="52" xml:id="d616fn52"
                        >Rudolf Hess, member of the German Reichstag, Minister without Portfolio;
                        Chairman of the Central Committee of the Nazi Party.</note> He is scheduled
                    to depart for Moscow tomorrow morning.</p>
                <p>According to a German official the party was a great success and Molotov who
                    speaks some German made an excellent impression on <pb facs="0592" n="580"
                        xml:id="pg_580"/> the Germans. The source said that all of the Russians gave
                    evidence of being sincerely pleased and satisfied with current developments in
                    Russo-German relations. He remarked that announcements of startling agreements
                    or new treaties should not be expected, and added this is only the
                    beginning.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
